OK, here's the design pattern you should follow. Your `fsm_iterator` already does this well, so let's use it as the template.

## The Standard 2-Block FSM Pattern

You want **two `always` blocks** plus combinational `assign`s:

### Block 1: `always @(posedge clk)` -- Registered state & data

This stores things that need to persist across cycles: the state register, intermediate computation results, and latched inputs. Everything here uses `<=` (non-blocking).

```verilog
always @(posedge clk) begin
    if (reset)
        current_state <= IDLE;
    else
        current_state <= next_state;

    case (current_state)
        IDLE: begin
            if (in_val) begin
                // latch inputs into internal regs
                a_reg <= a;
                b_reg <= b;
            end
        end
        CALC_0: begin
            // store multiply result from this cycle
            product_lo <= fpm_out;
        end
        // ...
    endcase
end
```

### Block 2: `always @(*)` -- Combinational outputs & next state (Mealy)

This is where you compute `next_state`, the handshake signals (`in_rdy`, `out_val`), the multiplier input mux (`fpm_in_a`, `fpm_in_b`), and the data output (`out`). Everything here uses `=` (blocking). Because it's combinational, these outputs react **within the same cycle** as the inputs that drive them -- that's what makes it Mealy and minimizes latency.

```verilog
always @(*) begin
    // defaults (prevents latches)
    next_state = current_state;
    in_rdy     = 1'b0;
    out_val    = 1'b0;
    out        = 27'sd0;
    fpm_in_a   = 18'sd0;
    fpm_in_b   = 18'sd0;

    case (current_state)
        IDLE: begin
            in_rdy = 1'b1;
            if (in_val && !is_high_resolution) begin
                // Low-res: feed a,b directly to the 18-bit multiplier,
                // output is ready combinationally THIS cycle
                fpm_in_a = a[17:0];
                fpm_in_b = b[17:0];
                out_val  = 1'b1;
                out      = {9'b0, fpm_out[35], fpm_out[30:14]};
                // stay in IDLE -- zero-cycle turnaround
            end
            else if (in_val && is_high_resolution) begin
                next_state = CALC_0;
                // set up first multiply for Karatsuba
                fpm_in_a = AL;
                fpm_in_b = BL;
            end
        end
        CALC_0: begin
            // AL*BL result is in fpm_out (combinational from registered inputs)
            // set up next multiply
            fpm_in_a = AH;
            fpm_in_b = BH;
            next_state = CALC_1;
        end
        // ... more Karatsuba states ...
        CALC_DONE: begin
            out_val = 1'b1;
            out     = final_result;
            if (out_rdy)
                next_state = IDLE;
        end
    endcase
end
```

## Key Principles

**1. Outputs (`out`, `out_val`, `in_rdy`) should NOT be registers -- declare them as combinational (`output reg` assigned in `always @(*)`).**

The `reg` keyword on an output just means "assigned in an always block." When that block is `always @(*)`, it's still combinational -- no flip-flop is inferred. This gives you minimum latency: the output responds in the same cycle as the state/input change.

**2. The multiplier inputs (`fpm_in_a`, `fpm_in_b`) should be combinational muxes.**

Just like your `fsm_iterator` does with `mult_in_a`/`mult_in_b` (lines 127-146). The combinational multiplier (`full_precision_mult_18_bit`) produces its result within the same cycle. So in each state you set up the mux, and the multiply result is available immediately in `fpm_out`.

**3. Internal intermediate values that need to survive across clock edges go in the registered block.**

For Karatsuba, you need to store partial products (like `AL*BL`, `AH*BH`) across cycles while you reuse the single multiplier for the next partial product. Those go in the `always @(posedge clk)` block.

**4. Always set defaults at the top of the combinational block.**

This prevents inferred latches. Your `fsm_iterator` does this on lines 93-95 (`next_state = current_state; in_rdy = 0; out_val = 0`).

## For Minimum Cycles

With this pattern and one 18-bit multiplier, Karatsuba needs 3 multiply cycles (AL\*BL, AH\*BH, (AL+AH)\*(BL+BH)) plus possibly 1 cycle to accumulate the final result. The low-res path can be zero additional cycles (combinational pass-through in IDLE). So you're looking at:

- **Low-res (18-bit)**: 0 extra cycles (combinational in IDLE, `in_rdy` and `out_val` both high same cycle)
- **High-res (27-bit Karatsuba)**: 3-4 cycles (3 multiplies + final accumulation)

The reason this is minimal: the Mealy combinational outputs let you overlap the "output ready" signal with the last computation state, rather than needing an extra DONE state just to present the result.

The `signed` removals look good. But there are still a few issues:

### 1. `AL`, `AH`, `BL`, `BH` syntax is still wrong (lines 242-245)

```242:245:c:\Users\ezrar\cornell-classes\Spring 2026\ECE 5760\Mandelbrot\fsm_iterator\fsm_iterator.v
    wire AL[16:0];
    wire AH[9:0];
    wire BL[16:0];
    wire BH[9:0];
```

This declares `AL` as a **1-bit wire with a 17-element unpacked array**, not a 17-bit vector. The bit range needs to go *before* the name:

```verilog
wire [16:0] AL;
wire [9:0]  AH;
wire [16:0] BL;
wire [9:0]  BH;
```

As-is, `{8'b0, AH}` and `{1'b0, AL}` would concatenate single bits, not 10-bit and 17-bit vectors. This would silently produce wrong results.

### 2. `fpm_in_a`, `fpm_in_b` are still `signed` (lines 219-220)

```219:220:c:\Users\ezrar\cornell-classes\Spring 2026\ECE 5760\Mandelbrot\fsm_iterator\fsm_iterator.v
    reg signed [17:0] fpm_in_a, fpm_in_b;
    reg signed [35:0] fpm_out;
```

These feed into `full_precision_mult_18_bit` which does `a * b` on signed inputs. This is correct for the **low-res path** (Q4.14 signed values). But for the **Karatsuba path**, you're feeding in unsigned magnitudes like `AH_extended`, `AL_extended`, `SA`, `SB`. Since you zero-extended them so the MSB is always 0, the signed multiply will treat them as positive, so it works out. This is fine -- just be aware that `SA` and `SB` must never overflow into bit 17 or the multiply will interpret them as negative. Since `AL` is at most 17 bits and `AH` is at most 10 bits, their sum fits in 18 bits with the MSB = 0. You're OK.

### 3. Regarding your question: are z0 and z2 signed?

In Karatsuba, you decompose `a * b` (where a, b are unsigned magnitudes) as:

- **z2** = AH * BH (unsigned * unsigned = unsigned, always positive)
- **z0** = AL * BL (unsigned * unsigned = unsigned, always positive)
- **z1** = (AL+AH) * (BL+BH) - z2 - z0 (can be derived from unsigned products, always positive)

Since you stripped the sign out beforehand and work with absolute values, **z0, z1, z2 are all unsigned/non-negative**. The `full_precision_mult_18_bit` output `fpm_out` is declared `signed [35:0]`, but since both inputs have MSB = 0, the product will always be non-negative. So the sign bit of `fpm_out` will always be 0 for the Karatsuba path, and you can treat the stored partial products as unsigned.

You re-apply the sign at the very end with `sign_out = sign_a ^ sign_b` when assembling the final 27-bit result.

### 4. One more thing: `low_res_mult_out` width mismatch (line 217 vs 226)

```216:226:c:\Users\ezrar\cornell-classes\Spring 2026\ECE 5760\Mandelbrot\fsm_iterator\fsm_iterator.v
    wire signed [17:0] low_res_mult_in_a, low_res_mult_in_b;
    wire signed [17:0] low_res_mult_out;
// ...
    assign low_res_mult_out = {8'b0, fpm_out[35], fpm_out[30:14]};
```

`{8'b0, fpm_out[35], fpm_out[30:14]}` = 8 + 1 + 17 = **26 bits**, but `low_res_mult_out` is only `[17:0]` = **18 bits**. The upper 8 zero-padded bits get truncated, leaving just `{fpm_out[35], fpm_out[30:14]}` = 18 bits. That happens to be the right Q4.14 result, but the `{8'b0, ...}` padding is misleading and has no effect. 

Also, `low_res_mult_out` is declared `signed [17:0]` which is correct here since it holds a signed Q4.14 value (the low-res path doesn't strip signs).

Then on line 295 you assign `out = low_res_mult_out`, which puts an 18-bit value into a 27-bit signed output. Verilog will **sign-extend** it because `low_res_mult_out` is declared `signed`. This is actually the correct behavior for widening Q4.14 to Q4.23 -- sign extension preserves the value and the lower 9 fractional bits become zero. So that's fine, but you should remove the misleading `{8'b0, ...}` from line 226 and just write `{fpm_out[35], fpm_out[30:14]}`.

**10,013 / 10,013 passed, 0 failed.** The Karatsuba multiplier now produces bit-exact results matching the reference `signed_mult` across all 13 named test cases and 10,000 random vectors.

The fix was negating the full 54-bit unsigned product *before* truncating to Q4.23, rather than truncating then negating. This matches the 2's complement floor-toward-negative-infinity rounding behavior of the reference multiplier:

```253:254:c:\Users\ezrar\cornell-classes\Spring 2026\ECE 5760\Mandelbrot\fsm_iterator\fsm_iterator.v
    wire [53:0] p_signed = sign_out ? (~p_mag + 1'b1) : p_mag;
    wire signed [26:0] hi_out = {p_signed[53], p_signed[48:23]};
```
